Hazardous Waste GRI 30 6-2 Edwards defines hazardous waste as any waste with properties that make it dangerous or capable of having a harmful effect on human health or the environm ent.,EW_2020.pdf
"Included in this definition are all wastes which have hazardous characteristics of ignitability, corrosivity, reactivity and toxicity as well as other regulated wastes such as biohazardous and medical waste (including medical plastics) , electronic waste, fluorescent lamps, and batteries.",EW_2020.pdf
"Other waste materials maybe also be listed as specific hazardous wastes, if required by country or local regulation.",EW_2020.pdf
"In 2020, Edwards disposed of approximately 1, 746 metric ton s (MT) of hazardous waste from our sev en global manufacturing plants .",EW_2020.pdf
This represents an increase of 31% over prior year and an increase of 121% over our 2015 baseline year.,EW_2020.pdf
"While during the same periods, when normalized by revenue, ou r hazardous waste increased 30% year- over-year and only 26% from our 2015 baseline.",EW_2020.pdf
"Even though Edwards has continued to grow in both size and complexity, our hazardous waste generation has outpaced our growth and our five- year result did not match our aggressive long- term target to reduce hazardous waste disposal by 20% when normalized by revenue.",EW_2020.pdf
The increase in hazardous waste generation is primarily attributed to new products and enhancement of manufacturing equipment and processes which aggressively began in 2018 and continued through 2020.,EW_2020.pdf
"Validation of our manufacturing processes is required in order to meet stringent FDA and global medical device quality assurance regulations and involves thorough testing of our equipment, procedures, and chemicals in order to ensure efficac y.",EW_2020.pdf
"While validation activities represent growth and a bright future for our business, validation results in an increase in hazardous waste disposal without resulting financial benefit until the products are brought to market.",EW_2020.pdf
"In 2020, we had major validation activities occurring at four of our seven global manufacturing plants.",EW_2020.pdf
"All of these plants —Singapore, Irvine, Costa Rica, and Ireland—are part of our fast -growing Implant Valve Network.",EW_2020.pdf
"The largest relative increase in hazardous waste disposal was at our Irvine plant, where we saw an increase of 57% over the prior year associated with the development of new product and manufacturing technologies, followed by increases in Costa Rica of 41% and Singapore of 23%.",EW_2020.pdf
All of these increases are a result of investing in our Heart Valve Implant network ’s future product improvements and manufacturing innovations.,EW_2020.pdf
Our established Caribbean based Critical Care operations realized reductions over prior years with Puerto Rico decreasing by 3% and Dominic an Republic decreasing by 1 4%.,EW_2020.pdf
"Edwards Lifesciences 2020 EHS Report 37 Our total cost for hazardous waste disposal in 2020 was $1,622,000, an increase of $154,000 from 2019.",EW_2020.pdf
"From 2015 to 2020, our average hazardous waste disposal cost decreased 22%, from $1.18 per MT in 2015 to $0.93 per MT in 2020.",EW_2020.pdf
"This reduction i n cost is due to enhancing our partnerships and efficiencies with our hazardous waste contractors and by instituting processes to more effectively manage higher volume waste streams generated on- site, including the ability to dispos e of bulk production wastes used for beneficial reuse in fuels blendi ng.",EW_2020.pdf
"The overall impact of our year - over-year hazardous waste intensity and cost reductions has been approximately $795,000 in cost avoidance from 2016 to 2020.",EW_2020.pdf
"We recycle approximately 32 % of our hazardous waste, primarily through the energy recovery from high- BTU rated wastes, including manufacturing solvents , most of which are generated at our Costa Rica and Irvine locations .",EW_2020.pdf
Approximately 62% of our hazardous waste is incinerated in order to reduce future liabilities and risks to the community.,EW_2020.pdf
"Less than 2 % of our hazardous waste is not qualified for recycling, incineration or treatment and is disposed of in hazardous waste- authorized landfill s. Non- Hazardous Waste GRI 30 6-2 Edwards defines non- hazardous waste as any waste not managed as hazardous or regulated waste and includes non - hazardous waste which is both disposed and recycled.",EW_2020.pdf
"It primarily includes all wastes that are allowed to be disposed in local landfills, but also may include wastes that are otherwise required to be recycled by local governments .",EW_2020.pdf
"In 2020, Edwards disposed of approximately 2,944 metric tons ( MT) of nonhazardous waste from our seven global manufacturing locations , which represents a 17% reduction from our prior year of 3,547 MT.",EW_2020.pdf
"This figure includes all non- hazardous waste incinerated, treated, sent to landfill, AND recycled.",EW_2020.pdf
"When compared to our baseline year of 2015, we have increased absolute volumes of waste by 37% while Edwards revenue growth during this time period was 74%.",EW_2020.pdf
"Since 2015, Edwards has grown in size and revenue faster than we have increased our non-hazardous waste disposal .",EW_2020.pdf
"When normalized by annual revenue, Edwards has reduced non- hazardous waste disposal by 21% since 2015, thereby beating our five- year target to reduce generation by 20%.",EW_2020.pdf
The reduction in non- hazardous waste is attributed to numerous initiatives at our manufacturing plants as well as reductions in office and nonmanufacturing wastes while employees were working from home during COVID -19.,EW_2020.pdf
The largest impact of our recycling efforts came from significant reductions in recycling of our plastics and corrugate.,EW_2020.pdf
"While plastic recycling increased approximately 5% year -over-year, our corrugate recycling came to a standstill due to the impact of the COVID -19 pandemic and the shift to recycling of higher grade corrugate for the global packaging market.",EW_2020.pdf
We hope to s ee this impact rebound in the future years as the economy recovers from the COVID -19 pandemic and the need for recycling of our corrugate increases .,EW_2020.pdf
"In 2019, significant efforts began to reduce packaging waste from our high- volume commercial products and we are continuing these efforts today.",EW_2020.pdf
"We expect that in future years, we will start to see the impact of ongoing packaging waste reduction efforts.",EW_2020.pdf
"Edwards Lifesciences 2020 EHS Report 38 Our total cost for non- hazardous waste disposal in 2020 was $ 393,000.",EW_2020.pdf
"Since 2015, our nonhazardous waste disposal cost, excluding recycling, increased from $201 per MT to $213 per MT, or $12 per MT.",EW_2020.pdf
"The overall impact of our year - over-year non-hazardous waste and recycling intensity and cost reductions has been approximately $495,000 in waste disposal cost avoidance from 2016 to 2020.",EW_2020.pdf
Recycling Edwards recycles hazardous and non- hazardous waste streams whenever possible.,EW_2020.pdf
"While our primary focus is to reduce the overall quantities of waste generated, we understand the importance of ensuring was te is sent for recycling wherever possible.",EW_2020.pdf
